            <p>Pinhas, son of Yosef. Pinhas, son of Yosef qbr ῾mh. Kblyn</p>
         </div>
      <div type="edition" subtype="transcription_segmented"><p><w xml:id="jeru0180-1" xml:lang="arc">פינחס</w> <w xml:id="jeru0180-2" xml:lang="arc">בר</w> <w xml:id="jeru0180-3" xml:lang="arc">יוסף</w> <w xml:id="jeru0180-4" xml:lang="arc">פינחס</w> <w xml:id="jeru0180-5" xml:lang="arc">בר</w> <w xml:id="jeru0180-6" xml:lang="arc">יוסף</w> <w xml:id="jeru0180-7" xml:lang="arc">קבר</w> <w xml:id="jeru0180-8" xml:lang="arc">אמה</w> <w xml:id="jeru0180-9" xml:lang="arc">כבלין</w> </p>
</div>
</body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Ossuary has low feet and a broken and reconstructed flat lid. Ornamentation on the chest's front side consists of two metopes in zigzag frames and a triglyph transformed into a rooted palm tree, with zigzag semi-circles indicating ascending branches, mirrored by roots. Each metope contains a six-petalled rosette within concentric zigzag circles, with zigzags overlaying petals, and zigzag quarter-circles in outer corners. The chest's right side, similar, has a frame enclosing an encircled rosette. The first line of the inscription appears in the right-hand metope, the second above the rosette on the chest's right side, and the third is inscribed vertically at the right edge of the front side. קבר אמה can be read as "tomb [here, ossuary] of his mother" or as "buried [his] mother," with the meaning being the same. Pinchas' name attests that he had fulfilled his filial duty. Reference to a deceased woman as "X, mother of Y" occurs occasionally; this is similar. The third line is difficult to decipher; the first three letters might be כבל, which suggests the name כבלולה recorded at Murraba'at.</p>
         </div>
